      "text_result": "I've diagnosed and fixed the CI failure.\n\n## Root cause (bucket a \u2014 upstream change broke a Percona assumption)\n\nThe failing target `//jstests/percona/tde:core_tde_cbc` ran the upstream test `jstests/core/query/map_reduce/mr_bigobject_replace.js`. That test's server-side reduce function calls `assert.gte`, which **does not exist in the mozjs-wasm server JS scope**, so instead of the expected `BSONObjectTooLarge` failure it produced `JSInterpreterFailure` (code 139, `'assert.gte is not a function'`, `wasm:function` frames) \u2014 failing the assertion.\n\nUpstream tags exactly these tests `mozjs_wasm_unsupported`. resmoke auto-excludes them only after detecting a mozjs-wasm server via `mongod --version` (`configure_resmoke.py`), but in the Bazel remote-test runner that probe **times out** (log: `TimeoutExpired(['mongod','--version'], 10)`), so the exclusion is silently skipped even though the server *is* mozjs-wasm.\n\n`.bazelrc.psmdb` already documents this gap and adds a bazel-level `-mozjs_wasm_unsupported` tag filter \u2014 but that only drops whole tagged *bazel targets*; it cannot exclude an individual jstest selected *inside* a resmoke passthrough suite. So the TDE suites still ran the test.\n\n## Fix\n\nAdded `mozjs_wasm_unsupported` to `exclude_with_any_tags` in the eight Percona-owned TDE passthrough suite YAMLs that run upstream dirs (core / aggregation / sharding / replica_sets, cbc + gcm), with an explanatory comment. This reproduces what resmoke's engine detection would have injected.\n\nI generalized beyond the single failing suite by grepping all of `jstests/` for the tag and cross-referencing each suite's `roots` (core=4, aggregation=2, sharding=1 matching tests; replsets/backup/percona-tde=0). I intentionally left `requires_mozjs_wasm` tests running (they need the wasm engine) and did not touch suites with no matching tests beyond replsets (added there for consistency/future-proofing).\n\nResponse written to the specified JSON path with `status: \"fixed\"`.",
